05497nam a22009375i 9781487538101DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875381017 a10.3138/97814875381012doi  a(DE-B1597)570743  a(OCoLC)1163784732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a364.6609712231 aStrange, Carolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death Penalty and Sex Murder in Canadian History /cCarolyn Strange. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOsgoode Society for Canadian Legal History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Politics of the Death Penalty and the Problem of Sex Murder -- t2. Sex Fiends and the Death Penalty at the Turn of Canada’s Century -- t3. Contesting Convictions and Questioning Culpability between the Wars -- t4. Sexual Psychopathy and Penal Severity in the Post-War Era -- t5. Sexual Psychopathy, Insanity, and the Death Penalty under Scrutiny in the 1950s -- t6. Sex Murder in the Sixties and the Demise of the Death Penalty -- tEpilogue: The Problem of Sex Murder in the Shadow of Abolition -- tReflection on Sources and Methods -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPublications of the Osgoode Society for Canadian Legal History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Confederation to the partial abolition of the death penalty a century later, defendants convicted of sexually motivated killings and sexually violent homicides in Canada were more likely than any other condemned criminals to be executed for their crimes. Despite the emergence of psychiatric expertise in criminal trials, moral disgust and anger proved more potent in courtrooms, the public mind, and the hearts of the bureaucrats and politicians responsible for determining the outcome of capital cases. Wherever death has been set as the ultimate criminal penalty, the poor, minority groups, and stigmatized peoples have been more likely to be accused, convicted, and executed. Although the vast majority of convicted sex killers were white, Canada’s racist notions of "the Indian mind" meant that Indigenous defendants faced the presumption of guilt. Black defendants were also subjected to discriminatory treatment, including near lynchings. In debates about capital punishment, abolitionists expressed concern that prejudices and poverty created the prospect of wrongful convictions. Unique in the ways it reveals the emotional drivers of capital punishment in delivering inequitable outcomes, The Death Penalty and Sex Murder in Canadian History provides a thorough overview of sex murder and the death penalty in Canada. It serves as an essential history and a richly documented cautionary tale for the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCapital punishmentzCanadaxHistory. 0aLust murderzCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aSteven Truscott.  acapital.  aconvictions.  acriminal justice.  adeath.  agender.  ahistory.  alaw.  amurder.  apenalty.  apenology.  apsychiatry.  apunishment.  asex crime.  asexuality.  awrongful.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP Pilot eBook-Package 2020z97831106904534